            'If current generations have a duty not to bequeath to future generations a world significantly worse than the one they inherited, then business-as-usual carbon emissions constitute a violation of intergenerational justice — unless the non-identity problem shows that future generations cannot be harmed by our choices, since different choices would have produced different people.',
            'If wealthy nations bear greater responsibility for climate change by virtue of their historical emissions, then a just global climate regime would require them to contribute disproportionately to mitigation and adaptation costs — unless historical responsibility is complicated by the fact that the decision-makers responsible for past emissions are dead.',
